<item>
            <title>[OPENJPA-1440] Allow COUNT(*) instead of COUNT(t0.id) for simple queries as an option</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/OPENJPA-1440</link>
                <project id="12310351" key="OPENJPA">OpenJPA</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;SQL generated for &quot;select p for PObject p&quot; is SELECT COUNT(t0.id) FROM POBJECT t0&quot;. This is valid and according to JPQL spec which does not accept COUNT&lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/star_yellow.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, JDBC Drivers for legacy databases may not always support COUNT(columnName) as reported in &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;1&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;OpenJPA should support such cases with a boolean option DBDictionary.useWildCardForCount.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;1&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://n2.nabble.com/COUNT-t-to-COUNT-tc4176827.html#a4176827&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://n2.nabble.com/COUNT-t-to-COUNT-tc4176827.html#a4176827&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
